{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3706431,"name":"ScottRandallWay","username":"ScottRandallWay","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/73ab20/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-08-08T00:42:47.446Z","cooked":"

Still relatively new to Java Command programming, but we are making great progress. We have swerve code generated by Talon-X that is working great. We are driving about in field oriented mode. We even implemented turbo and precision speeds. The team is looking to implement two buttons (left and right) for strafing. These buttons would move the robot laterally relative to its current position slowly for alignment to score coral. Is there a pattern or technique recommended for doing this?

Thanks!
Scott

The easiest way you can do this is to give the drivetrain a command to drive with a ChassisSpeed with a dx and omega of 0 and a dy of however fast you want to drive and bind it to one button and provide the same speed but with a -dy and bind it to another.

The exact implementation really depends on your code and whether you want it to drive field or robot relative, but this is one of the easiest ways to do it.

The swerve request you’re looking for is RobotCentric. Just supply zero velocity in the x direction (forwards) and a positive value for y velocity if you want the robot to travel left and a negative value for rightwards travel (assuming you want to strafe relative to the robots heading, which is what strafe means, I think).
